<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Text and Font Styling Example</title>
    <style>
        /* Global text styles */
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            font-size: 16px;
            line-height: 1.6;
            color: #333;
        }

        /* Headings */
        h1 {
            font-family: 'Georgia', serif;
            font-size: 36px;
            font-weight: bold;
            text-align: center;
            color: darkblue;
        }

        h2 {
            font-family: 'Georgia', serif;
            font-size: 28px;
            font-weight: normal;
            text-align: left;
            color: darkred;
        }

        /* Paragraphs */
        p {
            font-family: 'Arial', sans-serif;
            font-size: 16px;
            color: #555;
            text-align: justify;
        }

        /* Links */
        a {
            color: darkgreen;
            text-decoration: none;
            font-weight: bold;
        }

        a:hover {
            text-decoration: underline;
        }

        /* Highlighted text with different font properties */
        .highlight {
            font-size: 18px;
            font-weight: bold;
            color: #c0392b;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <h1>Welcome to the Text Styling Demo</h1>
    
    <h2>Introduction</h2>
    <p>
        This is a paragraph demonstrating various text properties in CSS. 
        You can change the font family, size, weight, and alignment to create visually appealing text. 
        The following text is a link styled using CSS: 
        <a href="#">Click here to learn more</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Text Highlight</h2>
    <p>
        You can apply different font properties to emphasize certain text elements.
        For example, this is a <span class="highlight">highlighted text</span> with larger font size and bold weight.
    </p>

</body>
</html>
Explanation of the CSS Properties Used
Global Text Styles (body):

font-family: Arial, sans-serif;: The default font for the entire page is set to Arial, with a fallback to any available sans-serif font.
font-size: 16px;: The base font size is 16px, ensuring consistent sizing across the page.
line-height: 1.6;: Sets the spacing between lines of text to improve readability.
color: #333;: The default text color is a dark gray.
Headings:

h1 { font-family: 'Georgia', serif; }: The <h1> heading uses the Georgia font, a serif typeface, to make the title stand out.
font-size: 36px;: The font size is set to 36px for a large, prominent heading.
font-weight: bold;: The heading is bold to emphasize it.
text-align: center;: The text is centered on the page.
color: darkblue;: The heading text is colored dark blue.
For h2, the font size is smaller at 28px, and the text is aligned to the left. The color is dark red to distinguish it from the primary heading.

Paragraphs (p):

font-family: Arial, sans-serif;: The text in the paragraph uses Arial for better readability.
font-size: 16px;: The size is set to 16px for regular body text.
text-align: justify;: This aligns the text on both sides, creating a neat, block-like appearance.
Links (a):

color: darkgreen;: Links are styled in a dark green color.
text-decoration: none;: This removes the default underline from links.
font-weight: bold;: Links are bold to make them stand out.
a:hover: On hover, the link will have an underline, giving visual feedback to the user.
Highlighted Text (.highlight):

font-size: 18px;: The text inside the <span> with the highlight class is slightly larger at 18px.
font-weight: bold;: The text is bold to emphasize it.
color: #c0392b;: The text color is set to a vibrant red to draw attention.
Conclusion
CSS provides powerful tools to style text and fonts, giving developers control over the appearance of headings, paragraphs, links, and other text elements. By adjusting properties like font-family, font-size, font-weight, text-align, and others, you can create aesthetically pleasing and readable web pages. For efficient and maintainable styling, external stylesheets or class-based CSS rules are typically preferred over inline styles.